\section{Fiscal Analysis: Dynamic Tariff Revenue Forecast}

\subsection{Theoretical Framework: The Dynamic Laffer Effect}
The relationship between tariff rates and fiscal revenue is governed by the Laffer Curve mechanism. However, trade volume does not react instantaneously to tariff shocks. We propose a \textbf{Dynamic Response Model} that distinguishes between short-term rigidity (contractual obligations) and medium-term elasticity (supply chain substitution).

The tariff revenue $R_t$ at time $t$ is defined as:
\begin{equation}
    R_t = V_t(\tau) \times \tau_t
\end{equation}
where $V_t(\tau)$ is the trade volume under tariff rate $\tau_t$. The core challenge is to model the time-varying decay of $V_t$.

\subsection{Baseline Prediction: SARIMA Model}
To establish a counterfactual baseline (imports without new tariffs), we employed the Seasonal AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average (SARIMA) model on historical U.S. total imports data (IMPTOTUS, 2008-2025).

\subsubsection{Data Preprocessing and Stationarity}
We performed the Augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) test on the logarithmic series of imports. The result (ADF Statistic: -1.8067, p-value: 0.377) indicated non-stationarity, necessitating first-order differencing ($d=1$) and seasonal differencing ($D=1$, $s=12$).

\subsubsection{Model Selection}
Through a grid search based on the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC), the optimal model structure was identified as $\text{SARIMA}(2, 1, 2) \times (1, 1, 1)_{12}$. The baseline forecast for the next 48 months is shown in Figure \ref{fig:baseline}.

